 - Adaptive Sketching and Validation for Learning from Large-Scale Data.jpg\" title=\"Picture - Adaptive Sketching and Validation for Learning from Large-Scale Data.jpg\" src=\"/static/cms/img/icons/plugins/image.png\" id=\"plugin_obj_7051\"></p>\n'),(7052,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7053,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7054,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7055,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7056,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7060,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7064,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7066,'<p>Enter your Content</p>'),(7068,'<p>Research in <a href=\"http://graphics.cs.yale.edu/\">computer graphics at Yale</a> includes sketching and alternative design techniques, material <img id=\"plugin_obj_7088\" title=\"Picture - VR-center\" width=\"380\" alt=\"Picture\" src=\"/static/cms/img/icons/plugins/image.png\" height=\"260\">and texture models, the role of models of human perception in computer graphics, and recovering shape and reflectance from images. Applications that drive this work are architectural design, cultural heritage documentation and analysis, and the study of biological forms. Computer graphics is one of the disciplines within <a href=\"http://cs.yale.edu/c2\">Yale C2</a>  (Creative Consilience of Computing and the Arts).</p>\n\n<p>Computer graphics is used extensively in a wide range of domains—from feature film and games to medical visualization and financial analysis. However impressive the growth of computer graphics applications has been over the past forty years, the goal of easily authoring computer graphics models input remains elusive. At Yale, the research in modeling includes sketching systems for early conceptual design and the capture and editing of digital models of existing physical objects at a range of scales—from entire buildings to individual objects.</p>\n\n<p>Computer graphics models need to include material appearance properties as well as geometry. Unfortunately, the models widely used in computer graphics assume that the materials are both pristine and immutable, even though real materials are neither. The goal of research on material and texture models at Yale is to devise new material representations and expressive interfaces for editing such representations, to develop novel methods to simulate materials and the processes that affect their appearance, and to physically measure the input required for material models.</p>\n\n<p>Faculty members working in this area are Julie Dorsey and Holly Rushmeier.</p>\n'),(7076,'<p><strong>Ph.D:  </strong>The Chinese University of Hong Kong</p>\n\n<p><strong>Tel: </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Email:  </strong>liuxp@@shanghaitech.edu.cn</p>\n\n<p><strong>Office:  </strong>Room 302, Building 8</p>\n\n<p><strong>Homepage:  </strong>http://sist.shanghaitech.edu.cn/faculty/liuxp/</p>\n'),(7077,'<p><strong>Ph.D:  </strong>The Chinese University of Hong Kong<br>\n<strong>Tel: </strong><br>\n<strong>Email:  </strong>liuxp@@shanghaitech.edu.cn<br>\n<strong>Office:  </strong>Room 302, Building 8<br>\n<strong>Research Interests:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Computer Graphics (Fluid Simulation and Rendering)</li>\n	<li>Fluid Dynamics (Visual Computing and Analysis)</li>\n	<li>Scientific Visualization</li>\n	<li>Image Analysis and Synthesis</li>\n	<li>GPU-based Parallel Computing<br>\n	 </li>\n</ul>\n'),(7078,'<p><strong>RESEARCH INTERESTS</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n \n <li>\n \n Computer Graphics (Fluid Simulation and Rendering)\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Fluid Dynamics (Visual Computing and Analysis)\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Scientific Visualization\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Image Analysis and Synthesis\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n GPU-based Parallel Computing<br>\n \n <br>\n \n </li>\n \n </ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>BIOGRAPHY</strong></p>\n\n<p></p><p>\n \n Dr. Xiaopei Liu is an assistant professor at the School of Information Science and Technology, ShanghaiTech University. He eceived Ph.D. degree on computer science and engineering from the Chinese University of Hong Kong, and later did postdoctoral research as a Research Fellow at Nanyang Technological University in Singapore.\n \n </p>\n \n <p>\n \n His research interests are multidisciplinary on the areas of computer graphics, fluid dynamics, scientific visualization, and parallel computing. He have been intensively working with researchers on fluid dynamics and physics for such research. In addition, He have been interested in image analysis/synthesis techniques with a focus on illumination and texture analysis. He is also doing system and research work on the design and implementation of small unmanned aerial vehicles (S-UAV).\n \n </p><p></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>SELECTED PUBLICATIONS</strong></p>\n\n<p></p><ul>\n \n <li>\n \n Yulong Guo, Xiaopei Liu, Xuemiao Xu, A Unified Detail-Preserving Liquid Simulation by Two-Phase Lattice Boltzmann Modeling, IEEE Transactions on Visualization and Computer Graphics (TVCG), 2016, accepted for publication.\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Maneesh Mishra, Xiaopei Liu, Martin Skote, Chi-Wing Fu, Kolmogorov spectrum consistent optimization for multi-scale flow decomposition, AIP Physics of Fluids (POF), Vol. 26, No. 5, p.055106, 2014.\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Xiaopei Liu, Wai-Man Pang, Jing Qin, Chi-Wing Fu, Turbulence Simulation by Adaptive Multi-Relaxation Lattice Boltzmann Modeling, IEEE Transactions on Visualization and Computer Graphics (TVCG), Vol. 20, No. 2, pp. 289-302, February, 2014.\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Xiaopei Liu, Lei Jiang, Tien-Tsin Wong, Chi-Wing Fu, Statistical Invariance for Texture Synthesis, IEEE Transactions on Visualization and Computer Graphics (TVCG), Vol. 18, No. 11, pp. 1836-1848, November, 2012.\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Liang Wan, Xiaopei Liu, Tien-Tsin Wong, Chi-Sing Leung, Evolving Mazes from Images, IEEE Transactions on Visualization and Computer Graphics (TVCG), Vol. 16, No. 2, pp. 287-297, March-April, 2010.\n \n </li>\n \n <li>\n \n Xiaopei Liu, Liang Wan, Yingge Qu, Tien-Tsin Wong, Stephen Lin, Ch